"{\"uid\": \"dailyrecord.co.uk-news-local-news-raploch-minister-urges-critics-olympic-33430143\", \"text\": \"A Raploch minister has asked critics of a controversial banquet scene at the Olympics opening ceremony to get their priorities straight.  St Mark's Parish Church minister, the Rev Barry Hughes, suggested there were more serious things to be concerned about, including the impact of poverty of local children.  At the globally televised ceremony, Drag Race France host Nicky Doll and other drag queens from the franchise formed a tableau that some felt resembled Leonardo da Vinci's painting The Last Supper which depicts Jesus and his Apostles.  Some religious groups later condemned the ceremony, including the Catholic Church in France. Church leaders said it included \\\"scenes of derision and mockery of Christianity\\\", as the 1490s painting depicts Christ and the disciples.  Even US former president Donald Trump waded into the row, telling a Fox News host, the ceremony was a \\\"disgrace\\\" due to the controversial moment.  However, Raploch minister Rev Hughes took to social media, posting: \\\"Some Christians are for some reason getting very angry about this scene from the Paris Olympics opening ceremony.  \\\"As a Christian minister I am angry about a lot of things - the levels of child poverty in my parish, the number of young deaths we have had in Raploch this year, the opportunities kids here do not get which children elsewhere take for granted, etc.  \\\"There are far too many genuine things for us to be angry about, and to take steps to address, without manufactured outrage about something at the Olympics which, [as pointed out by another person's post], did not really happen anyway.  \\\"We need to get our priorities right.  \\\"To be honest even if it had been the Last Supper painting being recreated, at the end of the day it's a painting, and probably not a an accurate depiction of the Last Supper anyway!\\\"  A number of people commented online to support Rev Hughes' comments.  Mary Daykin said: \\\"Thank you Barry, the voice of reason and compassion (as always).\\\"  Shauna Campbell Pirie added: \\\"Very well said Barry Hughes. So, so true\\\".  Organisers for the Olympics event had suggested the tableau was not a nod to 'The Last Supper' but to the feast of Dionysus, the Greek god of wine, however they later apologised \\\"for any offence\\\".  In a press conference, a Paris 2024 spokeswoman insisted that the ceremony had been intended to foster tolerance adding: \\\"Clearly, there was never an intention to show disrespect to any religious group.\\\"  Referring to the ceremony's artistic director, she added: \\\"On the contrary, I think Thomas Jolly did try to intend to celebrate community tolerance. We believe this ambition was achieved. If people have taken any offence we, of course, are really sorry.\\\"  AtReach and across our entitieswe and our partners use information collected through cookies and other identifiers from your device to improve experience on our site, analyse how it is used and to show personalised advertising. You can opt out of the sale or sharing of your data, at any time clicking the \\\"Do Not Sell or Share my Data\\\" button at the bottom of the webpage. Please note that your preferences are browser specific. Use of our website and any of our services represents your acceptance of the use ofcookiesand consent to the practices described in ourPrivacy NoticeandTerms and Conditions.\"}"